<p>Express the radical as a power with a rational exponent,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	2^{x^2+x-\frac{11}{2}} &amp;= 2^{1/2}
\end{align*}\]

<p>Then equate its exponents,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	x^2+x-\frac{11}{2} &amp;= \frac{1}{2} \\
	2x^2+2x-11 &amp;= 1 \\
	2x^2+2x-12 &amp;= 0 \\
	(2x-4)(x+3) &amp;= 0 \\
	(x-2)(x+3) &amp;= 0 \\
\end{align*}\]

<p>Hence,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	x =2 \quad or \quad x=-3    \tagans
\end{align*}\]

